**Description**
When de serializing an object containing a UUID it fails, because it tries to parse the byte array as string.

 > tools.jackson.databind.exc.InvalidFormatException: Cannot deserialize value of type `java.util.UUID` from String "[B@38db8089": UUID has to be represented by standard 36-char representation

**Minimal reproducer**
Please provide the smallest possible code example that demonstrates the problem:

```java
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;

import de.undercouch.bson4jackson.BsonFactory;
import java.util.UUID;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import tools.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import tools.jackson.databind.json.JsonMapper;

class Bson4JacksonUuidReproTest {

  record Holder(UUID id) {}

  @Test
  void uuidRoundTripsThroughBsonBinary() {
    ObjectMapper mapper = JsonMapper.builder(new BsonFactory()).build();
    Holder original = new Holder(UUID.randomUUID());

    byte[] bson = mapper.writeValueAsBytes(original);
    try {
      Holder restored = mapper.readValue(bson, Holder.class);
      assertEquals(original, restored);
    } catch (RuntimeException e) {
      System.out.println("REPRO-EXCEPTION-TYPE: " + e.getClass().getName());
      System.out.println("REPRO-EXCEPTION-MSG: " + e.getMessage());
      throw e;
    }
  }
}
```

**Expected behavior**
The above test not to fail

**Actual behavior**
Test fails

**Versions**
- bson4jackson version: 3.1.0
- Jackson version: 3.1.4
- Java version: 25.0.3

Our current workaround
```java
public final class BsonUuidDeserializer extends UUIDDeserializer {

  @Override
  public UUID deserialize(JsonParser p, DeserializationContext ctxt) {
    if (p.currentToken() == JsonToken.VALUE_EMBEDDED_OBJECT) {
      return this._deserializeEmbedded(p.getEmbeddedObject(), ctxt);
    }
    return super.deserialize(p, ctxt);
  }
}
```

Hi, I'm trying to serialize plain POJOs directly to BSON to insert into a mongodb database, and I'm having problems with fields that are typed as long (primitive).

With the following Java example:

```
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import com.mongodb.client.MongoClient;
import com.mongodb.client.MongoClients;
import com.mongodb.client.MongoCollection;
import com.mongodb.client.MongoDatabase;

import de.undercouch.bson4jackson.BsonFactory;

import org.bson.Document;
import org.bson.RawBsonDocument;

import java.io.ByteArrayOutputStream;
import java.io.IOException;

// POJO class
class User {
	public int intAge;
	public long longAge;
	public User(final int age) {
		intAge = age;
		longAge = age;
	}
}

public class MongoDBInsertExample {

	public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
		// Create a MongoDB client
		MongoClient mongoClient = MongoClients.create("mongodb://localhost:27017");
		MongoDatabase database = mongoClient.getDatabase("test");

		// Create a sample user
		final User user = new User(30);
		final MongoDatabase db = database;

		// Method 1: Using Jackson to generate JSON and then insert it via MongoDB API
		{
			final MongoCollection<Document> collection = db.getCollection("users_json");

			// Create an ObjectMapper for JSON
			final ObjectMapper jsonMapper = new ObjectMapper();

			// Serialize the user to JSON
			final String json = jsonMapper.writeValueAsString(user);

			// Parse the JSON string & insert the document into MongoDB
			collection.insertOne(Document.parse(json));

			System.out.println("Inserted using JSON: " + json);
		}
		final MongoDatabase db1 = database;


		// Method 2: Using Jackson and BSON4Jackson to generate BSON in a buffer
		{
			final MongoCollection<RawBsonDocument> collection = db1.getCollection("users_bson", RawBsonDocument.class);

			// Create an ObjectMapper for BSON
			final ObjectMapper bsonMapper = new ObjectMapper(new BsonFactory());

			// Serialize the user to BSON
			final ByteArrayOutputStream baos = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
			bsonMapper.writeValue(baos, user);

			// Creat the Raw BSON document & insert it into MongoDB
			collection.insertOne(new RawBsonDocument(baos.toByteArray()));

			System.out.println("Inserted using BSON buffer: " + user);
		}

		// Close the MongoDB client
		mongoClient.close();
	}

}
```

when I look at the MongoDB console (mongosh) for those collections:

```
use test

test> db.users_json.find()
[
  {
    _id: ObjectId('6986139664a3f08bcb643b2f'),
    intAge: 30,
    longAge: 30
  }
]

test> db.users_bson.find()
[
  {
    _id: ObjectId('6986139681550163bf1c7ce0'),
    intAge: 30,
    longAge: Long('30')
  }
]
```

The BSON version gives me the long value as a Long() object. Is there a way to have Long() as an int64 value or at least the same output than for JSON ?

I am running bson4jackson-2.18.0 and jackson-2.20 (and bson-5.6.2 if it helps).

Thanks in advance

