Hi!

Several years back I reported #72 which was sort of resolved but replaced by a new issue that has remained, so I'll report it separately.

Given a polymorphic class with Jackson annotations like

```kt
@JsonTypeInfo(
    use = JsonTypeInfo.Id.NAME,
    include = JsonTypeInfo.As.PROPERTY,
    property = "type",
    visible = true)
@JsonSubTypes(
    JsonSubTypes.Type(value = ADoc::class, name = "a"),
    JsonSubTypes.Type(value = BDoc::class, name = "b"),
)
abstract class BaseTestDoc {
    var _id: ObjectId? = null
    abstract val type: String
    var created: Date? = null
}

class ADoc : BaseTestDoc() {
    override val type = "a"
}

class BDoc : BaseTestDoc() {
    override val type = "b"
}
```

When parsing BSON where the `type` comes after the date `created`, the date is ignored

```kt
        val bson = jongoBsonOf(
            "_id" to _id,
            "created" to created,
            "type" to type,
        )

        bson.parseJongoBson<BaseTestDoc>().also {
            it as ADoc
            it.type shouldEqual type

            // If type comes after date this fails with jongo:1.4.0 - 1.5.1, bson4jackson:2.9.0 - 2.15.1
            it.created shouldEqual created
        }
```

It seems that this normally wouldn't be an issue as eg ADoc above would be serialized with `type` defined first, but when using jongo and bson4jackson to parse data from MongoDB the properties could potentially be rearranged by another process or person and cause the problem.

Complete test to reprodice the problem is defined in [this gist](https://gist.github.com/lovef/0bdc537d3a066145c2d8698d7d9d38f4)

I've have some streaming code that does strict validation that is failing w/ BsonParser. The issue is that the transition from END_OBJECT to null does not set getCurrentToken().

I expect that `parser.nextToken() == parser.currentToken()` to always be true:

```java
    public static void checkParser(JsonParser parser) throws IOException {
        JsonToken token;
        while ((token = parser.nextToken()) != null) {
            assertThat(parser.currentToken()).isEqualTo(token);
        }
        assertThat(parser.currentToken()).isNull();
    }
```

This appears to be a bug with all 2.15.x versions of jackson mapper. Using 2.14.3 this does not break. As the title implies, it seems to be a very very specialized situation that breaks but is annoying because it prevents me from reading data out of mongo as a result. I'll start by pasting the full source code for how to reproduce this issue locally and then explain my findings.

```kotlin
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonSubTypes
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonTypeInfo
import org.litote.kmongo.KMongo
import org.litote.kmongo.deleteMany
import org.litote.kmongo.getCollection
import org.litote.kmongo.withDocumentClass
import kotlin.random.Random

fun main() {
    val db = KMongo.createClient("mongodb://localhost/test").getDatabase("test")

    val table = db.getCollection<Fiddle>()
    table.deleteMany()
    table.insertOne(Fiddle(Matrix(listOf(Random.nextDouble()))))

    table.withDocumentClass<Fiddlestix>().find().forEach { println(it) }
    table.find().forEach { println(it) }
}

data class Fiddle(val stix: Matrix)
data class Fiddlestix(val stix: Stix)
data class Stix(val type: Block.Type, val matrix: List<Double>)

@JsonTypeInfo(
    use = JsonTypeInfo.Id.NAME,
    include = JsonTypeInfo.As.EXISTING_PROPERTY,
    property = "type",
    visible = true
)
@JsonSubTypes(
    JsonSubTypes.Type(value = Matrix::class, name = "Matrix"),
)
sealed class Block(val type: Type) {
    enum class Type { Matrix, Text }
}
data class Text(val md: String) : Block(Type.Text)
data class Matrix(val matrix: List<Double>) : Block(Type.Matrix)

```

This creates a record in mongo that looks like 
```
  {
    _id: ObjectId("653bf5ecd008b1551c398130"),
    stix: { matrix: [ 0.9386461023778372 ], type: 'Matrix' }
  }
```

When it goes to read it as a `Fiddlestix` definition (non sealed class), it reads fine. When it is read as a `Fiddle` definition (sealed class/inheritence version) when it gets to the matrix part of it, it breaks with the exception
```
Exception in thread "main" java.lang.RuntimeException: com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonMappingException: empty String (through reference chain: app.playerzero.iris.Fiddle["stix"]->app.playerzero.iris.Matrix["matrix"]->java.util.ArrayList[0])
```

What is more interesting is that if I edit the mongo record so that `type` is before the `matrix` value as such
```
  {
    _id: ObjectId("653bf5ce0a7faf1c9bde8610"),
    stix: { type: 'Matrix', matrix: [ 0.8264975134720011 ] }
  }
```
both data models of the code read the data just fine. It appears to be an issue related to it not knowing the type of object that it is reading the list of doubles into. It doesn't happen if the field is a String, another complex object, number, or other things, only if it is a list (possibly only if a list of primitives even but didn't test that).


Also interesting is that if I change the sealed class definition to remove the @JsonTypeInfo
```
@JsonSubTypes(
    JsonSubTypes.Type(value = Matrix::class, name = "Matrix"),
)
sealed class Block(val type: Type) {
    enum class Type { Matrix, Text }
}

data class Text(val md: String) : Block(Type.Text)
data class Matrix(val matrix: List<Double>) : Block(Type.Matrix)
```
It also reads just fine.  Something about stating which property it has to read in order to understand which sealed class instance type it should be is breaking if there is a list of doubles before it is able to get to that type it looks like.

